d, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1360–1380":"1360–1380","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1332–1356":"1332–1356","1336–1416":"1336–1416","1336":"1336","1379":"1379","1356":"1356","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1416":"1416","Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1360–1380":"1360–1380","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1332–1356":"1332–1356","1336–1416":"1336–1416","1336":"1336","1379":"1379","1356":"1356","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1416":"1416","Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bailey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status name for a steward or official, from Middle English <i>bailli</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>baillis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>, an adjectival derivative of <i>baiulus</i> ‘attendant, carrier, porter’).","English: habitational name from Bailey in Little Mitton, Lancashire, named with Old English <i>beg</i> ‘berry’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, from Middle English (Old French) <i>bailli</i> ‘outer courtyard of a castle’ (Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’, a derivative of <i>bailer</i> ‘to enclose’). This term became a placename in its own right, denoting a district beside a fortification or wall, as in the case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."],"variants":[{"name":"Bailly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Emile, Marcel, Philippe.","French: occupational name for a steward or official, from Old French <i>baillif</i>. Compare   Bailey   4.","French: habitational name from (Le) Bailly, the name of several places in the northern part of France."]},{"name":"Bale","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, Middle English <i>bailli</i>, <i>baile</i>, from Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’ (see   Bailey   3).","Breton (<b>Balé</b>): variant of   Balay  .","French: unexplained."]},{"name":"Baily","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Bayly","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Bayley","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Balay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Rajesh, Satish.","Altered form of English   Bailey  .","French: habitational name from any of various minor places so named."]},{"name":"Baile","meanings":["Spanish: status name for a steward or official, from Old Spanish <i>baile</i>, Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>; cognate with English   Bailey  .","French (southern): variant of   Bail  .","English: variant of   Bale  ."]},{"name":"Baillie","meanings":["Scottish:","from Older Scots <i>baillie</i>, <i>baili</i>. In Scotland, a baillie was a status name for any of various officials, including the chief magistrate in a barony and (later) the chief magistrate or administrative officer of a barony or district. Etymologically, this is the same word as English   Bailey  , but the functions as well as the spelling of the two officials were different in England and Scotland.","topographic name from Older Scots <i>bailli</i> ‘outer court of a castle’; see   Bailey   3 and   Bale   1."]},{"name":"Baley","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Bailey was born in 1360, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Walter Bailey, was 28 and her mother, Mrs. Margaret Bailey, was 24. She married James Heyward in 1379, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1380, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1360–1380":"1360–1380","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1332–1356":"1332–1356","1336–1416":"1336–1416","1336":"1336","1379":"1379","1356":"1356","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1416":"1416","Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1360–1380":"1360–1380","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1332–1356":"1332–1356","1336–1416":"1336–1416","1336":"1336","1379":"1379","1356":"1356","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1416":"1416","Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdi